WEBVTT

00:00:00.960 --> 00:00:10.160
<v Speaker 1>So we've seen how we can use the present to talk about the future in Spanish using boy a vamos a or using some future context.

00:00:09.740 --> 00:00:15.740
<v Speaker 1>Pronto, soon, mañana, tomorrow, la semana que viene, the week that comes next week.

00:00:15.740 --> 00:00:19.660
<v Speaker 1>But we can also use the present in Spanish to talk about the past.

00:00:19.539 --> 00:00:21.539
<v Speaker 1>Just as we can in English.

00:00:21.539 --> 00:00:28.099
<v Speaker 1>In English and in Spanish, we have three ways to talk about the past, or three main ways to talk about the past.

00:00:28.320 --> 00:00:31.600
<v Speaker 1>We can say, for example, I ate.

00:00:31.600 --> 00:00:34.480
<v Speaker 1>We can say I was eating.

00:00:34.480 --> 00:00:38.320
<v Speaker 1>And we can say I have eaten.

00:00:38.320 --> 00:00:43.360
<v Speaker 1>Now when we say I have eaten, we're using I have, which is the present.

00:00:43.360 --> 00:00:48.320
<v Speaker 1>And then eaten is like a version of the verb, which is kind of complicated in English.

00:00:48.320 --> 00:00:52.960
<v Speaker 1>You say I have eaten, I have gone, I have wanted.

00:00:52.880 --> 00:00:55.920
<v Speaker 1>wanted, eaten, gone, they're all very different.

00:00:55.920 --> 00:00:58.720
<v Speaker 1>So that's kind of complicated in English how to build that.

00:00:58.720 --> 00:01:01.280
<v Speaker 1>But in Spanish it's very simple.

00:01:00.760 --> 00:01:05.479
<v Speaker 1>So we have I ate, I was eating, and I have eaten.

00:01:05.479 --> 00:01:10.040
<v Speaker 1>This I have eaten is going to be the first past that we learn

00:01:09.600 --> 00:01:11.280
<v Speaker 1>And we're actually using the present.

00:01:11.280 --> 00:01:13.119
<v Speaker 1>Now this have is not tener.

00:01:13.119 --> 00:01:19.360
<v Speaker 1>Tener we use for possession and we use with the combination of ke to give this meaning of have to.

00:01:19.580 --> 00:01:27.820
<v Speaker 1>Now, the verb that we use for have in the sense of I have eaten, I have gone, in Spanish it's haber.

00:01:27.640 --> 00:01:34.600
<v Speaker 1>Aber H A B E R and of course we have the silent H there in Aber.

00:01:34.600 --> 00:01:39.640
<v Speaker 1>Aber is to have in the sense of I have eaten, but Aber is extremely irregular.

00:01:39.420 --> 00:01:41.020
<v Speaker 1>There is no abo.

00:01:41.020 --> 00:01:42.780
<v Speaker 1>It's extremely irregular.

00:01:42.780 --> 00:01:48.380
<v Speaker 1>But there is a very easy way we can remember all of the versions of aber, even though it's very irregular.

00:01:48.380 --> 00:01:53.979
<v Speaker 1>What are the two vowel sounds that we have inside of the verb aber?

00:01:54.140 --> 00:01:55.580
<v Speaker 2>A and e.

00:01:55.580 --> 00:01:55.980
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:01:55.980 --> 00:02:02.060
<v Speaker 1>We have a and e inside the word aber and we're going to use that to help us remember the versions.

00:02:02.060 --> 00:02:03.580
<v Speaker 1>Let's start with e.

00:02:03.880 --> 00:02:07.560
<v Speaker 1>E all by itself means I have.

00:02:07.560 --> 00:02:09.640
<v Speaker 1>It's spelt He-E.

00:02:09.640 --> 00:02:15.320
<v Speaker 1>And of course we have the silent H there from Aber in E H-E.

00:02:15.320 --> 00:02:16.200
<v Speaker 1>I have

00:02:16.740 --> 00:02:22.980
<v Speaker 1>We actually saw already one other verb that forms its I version in this way.

